{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17566556","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17566556"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:43:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:43:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18842"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18842","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18842"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.04,0.13,0.78,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11575"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92805"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11575","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11575"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18842"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76164"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"203"},{"type":"tags","id":"1306"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"3016"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11260"},{"type":"tags","id":"11282"},{"type":"tags","id":"11299"},{"type":"tags","id":"12867"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27243"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27247"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36664"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92805","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92805"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA General Practitioner works as the solo doctor in a rural town that has limited medical services. The practitioner\u0027s teenage child has been experiencing anxiety and the doctor believes a prescription for diazepam will help with panic attacks.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate course of action?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Provide the prescription for diazepam due to limited local services","Await next trip to larger city to book an appointment with another General Practitioner","Document carefully and prescribe under supervision of Practice Manager","Engage appropriate Telehealth psychiatry services for assessment and management","Request permission from medical board to treat family"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate action is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eengage appropriate Telehealth psychiatry services for assessment and management\u003C/strong\u003E. Treating family members compromises professional objectivity and boundaries. This is particularly important when prescribing psychotropic medications or drugs of dependence. Telehealth provides a viable solution when local services are limited.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options are problematic because:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProvide the prescription for diazepam due to limited local services\u003C/strong\u003E - Limited access to healthcare does not override the importance of maintaining professional boundaries when it comes to prescribe Schedule 8, psychotropic medication and/or drugs of dependence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAwait next trip to larger city to book an appointment with another General Practitioner\u003C/strong\u003E - Delaying mental health care is inappropriate when more immediate options like Telehealth are available\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDocument carefully and prescribe under supervision of Practice Manager\u003C/strong\u003E - Documentation and supervision do not resolve the fundamental ethical issue of treating family members\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERequest permission from medical board to treat family\u003C/strong\u003E - Medical boards generally prohibit treating family members except in emergencies which is not the case in this situation. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile emergency situations may necessitate providing care to family members, ongoing care and especially prescribing of psychotropic medications should be provided by an independent practitioner to maintain professional boundaries and ensure objective clinical decision-making. Telehealth services provide an appropriate solution in rural settings with limited local options.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Medical practitioners should avoid providing care to people with whom they have close personal relationships due to compromised objectivity and professional boundaries.","Prescribing Schedule 8 medications or performing elective procedures for close contacts is inappropriate and potentially unethical.","Telehealth services provide an appropriate alternative when local medical services are limited."],"references":["Medical Board of Australia. Good medical practice: a code of conduct for doctors in Australia [online]. 2020 [Cited 2025 Jan 15]. Available at: https://www.medicalboard.gov.au/codes-guidelines-policies/code-of-conduct.aspx.","AHPRA and National Boards. Guidelines: Telehealth consultations with patients [online]. 2023 [Cited 2025 Jan 15]. Available at: https://www.ahpra.gov.au/Resources/Information-for-practitioners-who-provide-virtual-care.aspx."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76164"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18842"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76164","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76164"},"attributes":{"createdAt"